[normal]3.3.1
[normal]              
[normal]The introduction of complicated new legislation (and some 55 pages of guidance) 
[normal]also sends out a mixed message with regards to the coinciding agenda 
[normal]to simplify
[normal] the UK tax administration.
[normal] 
[normal]As stated
[normal] above
[normal], the new legislation will create additional uncertainty and add another layer of complexity for businesses to have to deal with.
[normal]3.3
[normal].2
[normal]              
[normal]As stated in our response to the original consultation, 
[normal]a much simpler solution existed in that it 
[normal]would be possible for HMRC to challenge the status of members simply by 
[normal]removing any perceived presumption of self-employment and using existing case law.
[normal] However, the intention is to remove that perceived presumption and then introduce new legislation that is unsatisfactory (examples as to why being set out above). 
[normal]3.3.3
[normal]              
[normal]This point comes into sharp focus when one considers that HMRC will have to continue 
[normal]to use existing case law when looking at LLPs formed outside the UK and traditional partnerships.  
[normal]3.3.4
[normal]              
[normal]Ironically, and not strictly a tax point, for the purposes of pension auto-enrolment, the test to determine who is within the ambit of the rules is wh
[normal]ether the individual is either an employee or a worker. As stated above
[normal],
[normal] salaried members of LLPs will not be employees for all purposes and will not satisfy the employment test. It is understood that the tests, as recommended by the 
[normal]pensions
[normal] regulator, as
[normal] to whether an individual is a worker are the existing employed/self-employed tests. 
[normal]3.3.5
[normal]              
[normal]Furthermore, a
[normal]s these are essentially anti-avoidance measures, questions may be raised as to whether the GAAR 
[normal]could
[normal]/should
[normal] 
[normal]instead 
[normal]be applied to counteract the resp
[normal]ective tax advantages 
[normal]that the draft legislation is intended to counteract
