[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]While it is suggested in the con
[normal]sultation document 
[normal](at paragraph 3.55) that the use of profit and loss allocations
[normal], in particular,
[normal] may be outside the scope of these rules, it is 
[normal]underst
[normal]ood
[normal] that any uncertainty could be removed by the provision of specific guidance on the point in question.
[normal]&#xa0;[bold]4.1
[normal]              
[normal]HMRC's 
[normal]Tax Consultation 
[normal]Framework,
[normal] sets out the five stages to tax policy development:
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Stage 1 
[normal]              
[normal]Setting out 
[normal]objectives and identifying options.
[normal]Stage 2 
[normal]              
[normal]Determining the best option and developing a framework for implementation including detailed policy design.
[normal]Stage 3 
[normal]              
[normal]Drafting legislation to effect the proposed change.
[normal]Stage 4 
[normal]              
[normal]Implementing and monitoring the c
[normal]hange.
[normal]Stage 5 
[normal]              
[normal]Reviewing and evaluating the change.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.2
[normal]              
[normal]Referring specifically to the original consultation document, it was set out that "while there are some aspects of detailed policy design that are still open, this consultation is at stage 3 and is 
[normal]about ways to achieve the objectives stated in the consultation document while ensuring that the proposals do not have unexpected impacts."
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.3
[normal]              
[normal]Firstly,
[normal] only inviting comments from professional advisors (and other stakeholders) at this late stage will (ev
[normal]idently) give rise to practical issues
[normal]. 
[normal]Unfortunately, it would now appear that
[normal] the introduction of the new rules will be rushed into place
[normal],
[normal] without proper consideration. This should not be the case when introducing new law. This approach will inevitably g
[normal]ive rise to 
[normal]ineffective
[normal] legislation
[normal],
[normal] to the detriment of both the businesses affected, and to the integrity of, and general confidence in, the UK tax administration.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]              
[normal]Furthermore, 
[normal]it simply cannot be said that the consultation period has sufficiently d
[normal]ealt with a number of the 'unexpected impacts' that have arisen. As stated above, question 
[normal]marks remain over the practical implications of the introduction of the new rules in particular
[normal], while 
[normal]the significant uprating of the expected revenue yield (as ide
[normal]ntified in the Autumn Statement 2013 documentation) is clear evidence that HMRC had failed to fully appreciate the implications of what had been proposed. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.5
[normal]              
[normal]However, in this case, 
[normal]it would appear that 
[normal]HMRC 
[normal]has chosen to
[normal] ignore
[normal] 
[normal]the 
[normal]evident 
[normal]failings in i
[normal]ts approach
[normal]. Indeed, rather than accept that the under estimate was as a result of any apparent flaws in the proposals
[normal],
[normal] and seek to correct the position, as 
[normal]might otherwise 
[normal]be expected during an on-going consultation process, there would seem to be somethi
[normal]ng of a congratulatory tone to the announcement regarding the 
[normal]additional £1.9 billion in revenue it now expects to recover. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]5.1
[normal]              
[normal]In summary, the subjective nature of what has been proposed puts serious doubt over whether the 
[normal]legislation, as d
[normal]rafted, will operate as intended. 
[normal]Indeed, the significant uncertainty arising as a result of 
[normal]the proposed new rules
[normal] could effectively act to undermine 
[normal]the Government's overall objective of ensuring a 
[normal]balanced,
[normal] and competitive tax system.
[normal] 
[normal]5.2
[normal]              
[normal]As such, 
[normal]it 
[normal]is
[normal] strongly 
[normal]recommended that
[normal] the Government reconsider the proposals and, at the very least, consider delaying the introduction of the new rules to allow 
[normal]for a further period of consultation and analysis of all possible impacts.
